X can be a "variable term" or a "non-variable term".
If X is a "variable term" then whatever appears in the place of the metavariable X, e.g. "Val",
Predicates that have "Val" as argument work on what "Val" designates (which is a non-variable term).
- The variable name "Val" may designate a "fresh term" that can unify with anything.
Then "Val" is called a "fresh variable" -- or an "unbound" or "unconstrained" variable (sometimes a "free
variable" but that is bad usage)
- The variable name "Val" may designate a "nonfresh term" that can only unify with a subset of all
terms. Then "Val" is called a "non fresh variable" -- or a "bound" or "constrained" variable.
If X is a "non-variable term", e.g "f(g(a))", it stands for itself.
Predicates that have such a term as argument work on that term directly.
